body.plain:
Florida Georgia Line is an American country music duo composed of Brian Kelley (from Ormond Beach, Florida) and Tyler Hubbard (from Monroe, Georgia). In December of 2011, they signed a publishing/production/management deal with Big Loud’s Craig Wiseman, Kevin “Chief” Zaruk, Seth England (Big Loud) and Joey Moi.

On July 16, 2012, Florida Georgia Line signed with Republic Nashville, part of the Big Machine Label Group

description.plain:
The acronym H.O.L.Y. has a double meaning revealed by the line in the chorus, “high on loving you.”

The song is the first single to be released from their album Dig Your Roots, released on August 26, 2016.

https://twitter.com/FLAGALine/status/726016811465117698







This song was written by William Wiik Larsen, Nate Cyphert, and Mike Busbee, a.k.a. busbee—he’s also written for country artists like Garth Brooks and Rascal Flatts.

Florida Georgia Line rejected this song at first—they didn’t even listen to it all the way through.
Singer Tyler Hubbard told ABC Radio: “A couple weeks later, we just were both kind of like, ‘Have you been listening to that “H.O.L.Y.,” that song?’ We both kind of fell in love with it over those few weeks of living with it, and realized the power. Sometimes a song doesn’t hit you right away.”

This song nearly went to an unbeliebable artist. busbee told Rolling Stone: “There was talk of Justin Bieber doing the song, and we had actually recorded it with another artist. Word came out that FGL were really into it—honestly we would’ve never thought to pitch that to them. We wrote it in L.A.; the other two writers are pop writers predominantly.”

Hubbard and his partner in Florida Georgia Line, singer Brian Kelley, were advised by their non-musical partners to do this song. Hubbard told Billboard: “There were three instances where our wives asked us about ‘H.O.L.Y.,’ and when we said we were considering it for FGL, they said we had to cut it. We feel like the song is anointed.”

On the Storme Warren Show, Kelley pointed out this song’s religious vibe. “It’s a beautiful, love, kind of spiritual, kind of worship song. The title of our album and tour is called ‘Dig Your Roots.’ For Tyler and I, there’s nothing more genuine and real and diggin’ our roots than singin’ a love song that sounds kind of like a worship song.”

This song crushed it on the charts—it rose to #1 on Hot Country Songs and #14 on the Hot 100.

description.plain:
“Cruise” is a song recorded by American country music duo Florida Georgia Line. It was released in August 2012 as the first single from their extended play It'z Just What We Do.

It was written by group members Brian Kelley and Tyler Hubbard with Joey Moi, Chase Rice, and Jesse Rice.

It was included on their debut studio album for Republic Nashville, Here’s to the Good Times, which was released on December 4, 2012.

By April 2013, “Cruise” had become the best-selling song by a country duo in digital history.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8PvebsWcpto

description.plain:
The title track and third single from Florida Georgia Line’s second album, Anything Goes.

This song was released as the album’s third single on September 26, 2014.

The album itself, released on October 4th, 2014, opened at number one on the US Billboard Charts, with 197,000 copies sold. The album reached number 2 on the Canadian charts, with 16,000 in sales.

description.plain:
“Confession” is a song about reflecting on your past. Unlike most of their previous party anthems up to this point, this Florida Georgia Line single emphasizes more on contemplation and reflection.

It took about 75-100 takes until they were finally happy with the track.

Brian Kelley had this to say about the track:

Tyler and I have enjoyed a lot of special moments personally and professionally over the last couple of years, so we really relate to getting in your truck, driving and thinking about where you want to be. A lot of power can come from confessing things.

Tyler Hubbard echoed what Kelley said later:

It’s a crazy ride we’ve been on, and this song really hit home. In the middle of celebrations and successes, we have to remind ourselves that we’ve been blessed to be on this journey. ‘Confession’ makes you pause and think for sure.
